{"title_page": "Jeremiah Hayes (filmmaker)", "text_new": "{{BLP primary sources|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:Jeremiah Hayes.jpg|thumb|Jeremiah Hayes <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemapolitica.org/artists/jeremiah-hayes|title=Jeremiah Hayes|website=cinema politica|language=en|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>]]'''Jeremiah Hayes''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] film director, writer and editor.<ref>[https://www.cinemapolitica.org/artists/jeremiah-hayes \"Jeremiah Hayes\"]. ''[[Cinema Politica]]''.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://onf-nfb.gc.ca/en/our-collection/production-personnel/?type=liste-fonction&idF=realisateurs&numf=01&alpha=H&idp=21459&idSMF=1&nom=Jeremiah%20Hayes|title=National Film Board of Canada|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He is most noted as co-director, co-writer and the editor of the film ''[[Reel Injun]],''<ref name=\"Reel Injun, New York Times review\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/14/movies/14reel.html|title=Reel Injun, New York Times review|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> for which he won the [[Gemini Award]] for Best Direction in a Documentary Program at the [[25th Gemini Awards]] in 2010.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemapolitica.org/blog/network/reel-injun-wins-five-geminis|title=5 Geminis Cinemapolitica|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Hayes is also recognized for his work editing ''[[Rumble: The Indians Who Rocked the World]]'',<ref name=\":7\"/> for which he won the [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Editing in a Documentary]] at the [[6th Canadian Screen Awards]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kahnawakenews.com/rumble-documentary-wins-three-canadian-screen-awards-p2562-1.htm|title=3 Screen Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ''[[Reel Injun]]'' went on to win a [[Peabody Award]] for Best Electronic Media in 2011<ref name=\":1\" /> and ''[[Rumble: The Indians Who Rocked the World|Rumble]]'' won the Special Jury Award for Masterful Storytelling at [[Sundance Film Festival]] in 2017.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAs a director, his other credits include the films ''Elefanti'' (1989),<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://miff.com.au/festival-archive/films/id/19799|title=MIFF Archive:|website=MIFF 2019|language=en|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> ''Silence & Storm'' (1995),<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://onf-nfb.gc.ca/en/our-collection/?idfilm=32765|title=National Film Board Listing|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ''God Comes As a Child'' (1998),<ref name=\":5\">[http://playbackonline.ca/1999/05/03/25396-19990503/ \"And the nominees are. . .\"] ''[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]]'', May 3, 1999.</ref><ref name=\"Full film on YouTube\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0LNWtHHXBzg&t=16s|title=Full film on YouTube|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and ''The Prom'' (1998).<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://onf-nfb.gc.ca/en/our-collection/?idfilm=33710|title=National Film Board Listing|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHis other credits as an editor include such films as ''Tia & Piujuq'' (2018),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isuma.tv/tiaandpiujuq|title=\u144f\u140a \u140a\u14bb\u14aa\u14d7 \u1431\u1405\u152a\u1585 {{!}} Tia and Piujuq|last=|first=|date=|website=IsumaTV|language=en-CA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref> ''Above the Drowning Sea'' (2017),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://2018.miamifilmfestival.com/films/above-the-drowning-sea/|title=ABOVE THE DROWNING SEA|website=Miami Film Festival 2018|language=en|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref> ''[[Sol (film)|Sol]]'' (2014),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemapolitica.org/film/sol|title=Sol|website=cinema politica|language=en|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref> ''The Wolverine: The Fight of the James Bay Cree'' (2014),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotdocs.ca/archive/films/wolverine-the-fight-of-the-james-bay-cree|title=Wolverine: The Fight of the James Bay Cree - Hot Docs|website=www.hotdocs.ca|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref> ''Shekinah: The Intimate Life of Hasidic Women'' (2013),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cultmtl.com/2013/10/shekinah-explores-the-lives-of-hasidic-women/|title=Shekinah explores the lives of Hasidic women|last=Hillier|first=Kayla Marie|date=2013-10-28|website=Cult MTL|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref> ''The Last Explorer'' (2009), ''Inside the Great Magazines'' (2007),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://emro.lib.buffalo.edu/emro/emroDetail.asp?Number=3700|title=National Film Board of Canada|last=Government of Canada|first=National Film Board of Canada|date=2012-10-11|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref> ''Vendetta Song'' (2005),<ref name=\"nfb.ca\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nfb.ca/film/vendetta_song/|title=National Film Board of Canada listing|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and ''Unbreakable Minds'' (2004).<ref name=\"Culture Unplugged\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cultureunplugged.com/documentary/watch-online/play/3753/Unbreakable-Minds|title=Culture Unplugged|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\nIn 2010, Hayes was awarded a [[Gemini Awards|Gemini Award]] for Best Direction in a Documentary Program for his work co-directing on ''[[Reel Injun]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/14/movies/14reel.html?mtrref=www.google.com&gwh=A25CC7CFAA3E43E0F69A306AA3D9F503&gwt=pay&assetType=REGIWALL|title=Reel Injun, New York Times review|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2018, he would win the [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Editing in a Documentary]] for his work editing ''[[Rumble: The Indians Who Rocked the World|Rumble]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/25/movies/rumble-the-indians-who-rocked-the-world-review.html|title=Rumble, New York Times review|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'' ''[[Reel Injun]]'' won a [[Peabody Award]] for Best Electronic Media in 2011<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/independent-lens-reel-injun-on-the-trail-of-the-hollywood-indian|title=Independent Lens: Reel Injun: On the Trail of the Hollywood Indian|website=www.peabodyawards.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> and ''[[Rumble: The Indians Who Rocked the World|Rumble]]<ref name=\":7\" />'' won the Special Jury Award for Masterful Storytelling at [[Sundance Film Festival]] in 2017.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sundance.org/projects/rumble-the-indians-who-rocked-the-world|title=rumble-the-indians-who-rocked-the-world|website=www.sundance.org|language=English|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\nOther honors are listed in the filmography below.\n\n== Personal life ==\nBorn in [[Walnut Creek, California]] on April 18, 1966.\n\nGraduated with a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] (BFA) in Film Production at [[Concordia University|Concordia University Montreal]] in 1990.\n\nSon of [[Jeremiah F. Hayes]] who is recognized in the field of Electrical Engineering.\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Title        \n!Contribution            \n!Description\n!Honors\n|-\n|1989    \n|''Elefanti'' <ref name=\":3\" />\n|Director, Editor, Camera             \n|15 minute\ndocumentary\n\n''(TVO)''\n|  -Best Short Documentary, [[Melbourne International Film Festival]], 1990.\n\n-Best 16mm production, Montreal International Young Film Festival, 1990.\n\n-Special Commendation, [[Canadian Film Festival|Canadian Intern